    "# Research Question"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Is there a statistically significant relationship between the prestige of a film cast, measured by major award nominations and wins, and how the film is rated by viewers, measured by IMDb ratings, controlling for genre and release year?\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Background and Prior Work"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We are trying to determine if we can find a relationship between a movie cast's stardom level and the movie's performance. Films packed with celebrities often can gain a lot of initial interest in trailers and marketing as there are people that show up at movie theaters just to see a specific celebrity on the screen. However, factors like negative online ratings and word of mouth reactions can tank a movie's performance a lot more than any celebrity can boost it, so it is hard to determine for any given movie how well it will perform. We will look for long term trends to discover if celebrity status is a good enough sign of movie success or not. We will define ways to measure stardom and measure movie success.\n",
    "\n",
    "In \"A Quantitative Study on the Effect of Cast Member Celebrity on Film Success,\" researchers used a regression model and analyzed the top 20 grossing films from 2015-2019, so a total of 100 movies total. They discovered that increased celebrity status correlated with both increased revenue and improved public perception. We question the conclusion of this article as taking the top 20 grossing films can mislead analysis as it doesn't account for cases where a movie \"flops\" but has celebrities. The author notes constraints such as using only the top 7 actors/actresses in their stardom metrics. Moreover, the study uses the actor/actress's current stardom level, which does not work in cases where the movie makes the actor/actress famous post-release. We can address these issues by accounting for a larger amount of the cast in stardom and measuring the actor/actress's popularity at the time of movie release. Additionally, 100 movies is likely not a large enough sample size and these movies were pulled up until 2019; Now a lot of marketing is done through social media which was not such a big tactic back then. Therefore, we can try to acquire data from a greater amount of movies and also use more recent movies.\n",
    "\n",
    "Additionally, in \"The Power of Stars: Do Star Actors Drive the Success of Movies?\" the researchers examine whether hiring star actors measurably increases a film’s expected theatrical revenue, using prediction‑market data and stock‑market style reactions around casting announcements. The study finds that, on average, attaching a star adds a few million dollars to a movie’s expected box‑office, quantifying star power to 3‑million‑dollar increase in revenue rather than treating it as a vague marketing benefit. Elberse shows that this effect is not constant. The marginal impact of a new star is larger when the existing cast is already strong, meaning other members within groups are important rather than simple “one big name is enough” logic. By focusing on expected revenue before release, the paper frames stars as a costly but quantifiable investment whose value must be weighed against high salaries and profit participation. However, a \"star\" is defined as actors who already have HSX StarBonds, which requires at least two major roles. That excludes emerging talent and underestimates cases where a film itself creates a star which this paper ignores, a similar flaw to the one found in the first document.\n",
    "\n",
    "In determining how we determine \"prestige\" of a movie's cast, we came across \"Factors Affecting the Financial Success of Motion Pictures: What is the Role of Star Power?\" in which they coin the term \"star power\" for this metric. In this paper they describe using the number of nominations for Academy awards and average lifetime gross revenue of films involving the specific celebrity. Again, to avoid previously discussed issues, we wlil have to make sure we use these stats respective to the time in wihch the movie came out, not present day. This document also reveals some surprising findings like that the time of year of the movie's release didn't seem to matter, nor did the genre make a significant impact. We will still take these into account when analyzing these movies, as we can never be completely sure if there truly is no effect from these features. They end up acknowledging how subjective star power is given how everyone has their unique perception and is thus difficult to measure. This only reinforces the notion that we should find many different ways to measure stardom.\n",
    "\n",
    "We also found a similar project on Github, \"IMDb_ratings_analysis\" that goes more broad and tries to find multiple parameters for a movie's success, as well as predict if a movie is going to do well based on discovered factors. They even perform plot analysis as part of their analysis. We do not plan on going this far with our project, but these are good stretch goals to include. For now, we will just focus on the celebrity status of our movie casts.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- \"A Quantitative Study on the Effect of Cast Member Celebrity on Film Success\" (Kwan, Scheepers, 2022): * Finding: Using a cross-sectional regression model, this study found that while a star-studded cast significantly boosts commercial success (box office) and public perception (IMDb ratings), it has almost zero correlation with \"artistic merit\" (metacritic score). https://www.researchgate.net/publication/369955734_The_Fault_in_Our_Stars_A_Quantitative_Study_on_the_Effect_of_Cast_Member_Celebrity_on_Film_Success\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- \"The Power of Stars: Do Star Actors Drive the Success of Movies?\" (Elberse, 2007): * Finding:  Star power was quantified through two factors: economic reputation (average past box-office draw from the actor's prior five films) and artistic reputation (points from recent awards). Testing was done with regressions, interactions with existing cast strength, and robustness to alternative windows, star thresholds, and realized revenue validation. Concludes that they were not able to find a strong relationship between the stars in a movie cast and the revenue of the movie (and thus valuation of its film studio).\n",
    "https://www.hbs.edu/faculty/Pages/item.aspx?num=23770 \n",
    "\n",
    "- \"Factors Affecting the Financial Success of Motion Pictures: What is the Role of Star Power?\" (Jen-Yuan Yang, Geethanjali Selvaretnam) Finding: Star power was quantified through award nominations and economic success. They used the least squares regression model, and found no significant correlation to box office success. https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/~wwwecon/repecfiles/4/1501-ori.pdf\n",
    "\n",
    "- https://github.com/charfimohamed/IMDb_ratings_analysis "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Hypothesis\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We hypothesize that the prestige of a film cast will not have a statistically significant positive association with IMDb rating, after controlling for genre and release year. Although Kwan and Scheeper's research found a positive correlation between star level public perception through IMDb ratings, as mentioned in the background section, we have identified areas of improvement in their set up that could change our findings. Kwan and Scheeper also found a positive relationship between celebrity presence and commercial performance, but other research from Elberse and Yang found no strong relationship between these two variables."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Data overview\n",
    "\n",
    "Instructions: REPLACE the contents of this cell with descriptions of your actual datasets.\n",
    "\n",
    "For each dataset include the following information\n",
    "- Dataset #1\n",
    "  - Dataset Name: IMDB Movies Dataset\n",
    "  - Link to the dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/harshitshankhdhar/imdb-dataset-of-top-1000-movies-and-tv-shows\n",
    "  - Number of observations: 1000\n",
    "  - Number of variables: 16\n",
    "  - Description of the variables most relevant to this project: We will likely use the IMDb rating as the dependent variable in this project. The dataset also has a column for the top star, the 2nd star, 3rd star, and 4th star actors in the movie - we will use all of these to create a feature representing the \"strength\" of the star cast. We also may use the \"Gross\" variable that represents how much the movie grossed as an output variable to determine whether the strength of the cast influenced how much money the movie made.\n",
    "  - Descriptions of any shortcomings this dataset has with repsect to the project: The only thing this dataset doesn't really have is a metric for the strength of the star cast - we will have to engineer that feature manually.\n",
    "- Dataset #2 (if you have more than one!)\n",
    "  - Dataset Name: Movies Box office Dataset (2000-2024)\n",
    "  - Link to the dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/aditya126/movies-box-office-dataset-2000-2024\n",
    "  - Number of observations: 4955\n",
    "  - Number of variables: 13\n",
    "  - Description of the variables most relevant to this project: We will likely match the movies in the dataset with the ones in the previous dataset to explore the relationship between domestic % and foreign %. These are two variables in this dataset that may be confounding variables, as the percentage of movie revenue that is domestic vs foreign could be influenced by factors other than just the strength of the star cast. These variables could, conversely, demonstrate a strong correlation between star cast and movie revenue/rating, as people in foreign countries may be more willing to watch a Hollywood movie because of certain actors. \n",
    "  - Descriptions of any shortcomings this dataset has with repsect to the project: The dataset may not have all the same movies in the first dataset, so there may be a very small sample of movies that overlap in both datasets that we can use for our analysis. This dataset also does not have any star cast information - only percentage of revenue generated by domestic and foreign as well as the genre and year of the movie. \n",
    "\n",
    "We plan to combine these datasets by finding the overlapping movies and checking if there is a relationships between foreign and domestic % of revenue and the star cast strength, as well as explore whether the percentage of revenue generated in other countries could be a confounding variable."
   ]
  },
